<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-16T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-16T14:00:00-05:00" n="381" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d381">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4236: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="from">Wilson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-16T20:00:00+01:00">February 16, 1932—8
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 16—5:21 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>24. Following is memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_SA1">Sweetser</persName> of private meeting of Twelve this afternoon:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“The Twelve approved this afternoon the text of the communication
                                    to be made to Japan. That text was given to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SN1">Sato</persName> this evening with covering
                                    letter from <persName corresp="#p_PBJ1">Boncour</persName> as
                                    President of the Council for transmission to Tokyo. It will be
                                    published here probably tomorrow morning subject to any desire
                                    expressed by the Japanese.</p>
                                <p>This is the first communication that the Council has made to one
                                    party only in the dispute. The only change of substance
                                    introduced this afternoon was the inclusion of a reference to
                                    the Nine-Power Treaty suggested by the British.”</p></quote></p>
                        <p>See my 25, February 16, 9 p.m.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_WHR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>